I"+<h2 id="solution">Solution:</h2>

<p>We expand the recurrence to get a feel for it.</p>

\[\begin{alignat*}{3}
        &amp;T(n) &amp;&amp;= T(n - 1) &amp;&amp;+ \frac{n}{2} \\ \\ 
        &amp;T(n - 1) &amp;&amp;= T(n - 2) &amp;&amp;+ \frac{(n - 1)}{2} \\ \\
        &amp;T(n - 2) &amp;&amp;= T(n - 3) &amp;&amp;+ \frac{(n - 2)}{2} \\ \\
    \end{alignat*}\]

<p>Hence, we propose that</p>

\[T(n) = 1 + \sum_{i = 2}^{n} \frac{n}{2} = 1 + \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)\left(\frac{n - 1}{2}\right)(n + 2) = \frac{(n - 1)(n + 2)}{\]

<p>We can now prove this via induction on $n$. For the base case, consider $n = 1$. Clearly,</p>

\[T(1) = \frac{(1 - 1)1 + 2}{2} = \frac{2}{2} = 1\]

<p>For the inductive hypothesis (IH), assume that</p>

\[T(n - 1) = \frac{(n - 2)(n - 1) + 2}{2}\]

<p>Now, for the inductive step, we have</p>

\[\begin{alignat*}{3}
        T(n) &amp;= T(n - 1) &amp;&amp;+ \frac{n}{2} &amp;&amp;\text{ (by definition of $T(n)$) } \\
        &amp;= \frac{(n - 2)(n - 1) + 2}{2} &amp;&amp;+ \frac{n}{2}  &amp;&amp;\text{ (by IH) } \\
    \end{alignat*}\]
